					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">MottZilla wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">It's a joke about the quality and general sound of the lyrics. They are latin and you can find a rough translation of what they are saying. But if you look at the lyrics (Bells Frogs, etc) and listen it really does sound like it could be that.</div><br />Yeah at some point it sounds like they are saying Sephi is a transvestite,  which definitely sounds true.<br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">FF7 works similar to older consoles in that the sound processor uses samples to play the song rather than just streaming music from the disc since the disc must be free to load assets while in battle as every single asset cannot fit into memory at once. There is a trick to exploit this behavior too. You cast Regen on your party and then another spell and after regen is cast you open the CD lid and the battle will not proceed until it can load the new spell so you can regenerate all your health without fear of being attacked.</div>
<br />Cool ! Thanks for sharing this. Then I guess all samples (music and lyrics) fit in the memory at once ? Or does FF7 switch out some unused music samples out of memory to witch the lyrics in when playing one-winged angel ?
<br />
<br />The SPU has 512kb of memory, 508kb which are usable, and stores samples in a compressed way so that 14 16-bit samples are stored in 16 bytes, for a 1.75 compression ratio. At a playback rate of 44100 Hz this allows to store 508 * 1.75 * 1024 / 44100 = 20.6 seconds of samples which sounds pretty decent. The SNES can only store about 4-6 seconds (at 32000 Hz) depending on how much RAM you use for your sound code and echo buffer.</div>

					
						<div class="postbody"><br />_________________<br />Life is complex: it has both real and imaginary components.</div>
