				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">Yeah it looks like the only real big difference betweeh PS1 and SNES SPU is that the PS1 SPU has no code to run, it just play samples and is directly controlled by the main CPU. Since a PSF player emulate the main CPU, any "tricks" that would be done by overwriting sound memory during playback is emulated without problem, while on the SNES this implies communication between the SPU and the CPU by those 4 registers.
<br />
<br />And while the PS1's SPU is able to play 24 voices with reverb (as opposed to 8 voices with echo), and that the encoding sheme looks slightly different but really similar to BRR, it's really an updated SPC700.</div>

					
						<div class="postbody"><br />_________________<br />Life is complex: it has both real and imaginary components.</div>
