						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">Bregalad wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Yeah it looks like the only real big difference betweeh PS1 and SNES SPU is that the PS1 SPU has no code to run, it just play samples and is directly controlled by the main CPU.</div><br />So in other words, it runs in "Wario's Woods mode".<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">And while the PS1's SPU is able to play 24 voices with reverb (as opposed to 8 voices with echo), and that the encoding sheme looks slightly different but really similar to BRR, it's really an updated SPC700.</div>
<br />What do you expect? <a href="http://www.sony.net/Fun/SH/1-35/h2.html" class="postlink">It's a Sony</a>. Heck, I read somewhere that even MiniDisc would have used a BRR/VAG style codec instead of ATRAC had Philips not promoted <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/MPEG-1_Audio_Layer_I" class="postlink">MP1</a> to Sony.
<br />
<br />But then the PlayStation 2 went back to the structure of separate CPUs for the game program vs. sound.</div>

