				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">I believe you are wrong in saying "most" as I would say if there was one more dominant than the other it is sequenced music that is less common. Tons of games stream music. Mega Man X3, X4, X5, X6 all do. Oddly Mega Man 8 does not. Mortal Kombat II (japan only) uses sequenced music because they keep the CD free for in game loading. Mortal Kombat 3 uses redbook audio. Ridge Racer used it too. Twisted Metal 2 uses redbook audio. Wipeout I believe uses redbook or XA which is something I believe the PS1 MDEC decodes in addition to decoding FMV. 
<br />
<br />I wish I could think of some more but I really think it's much more common that games stream music off the disc in PS1 games than using sequenced music with samples. It really depends on the game design which they use. As I mentioned before, RPGs are alot more likely than an action game to use sequenced. But an action game (like Descent) generally loads all game resources for that level into memory and has no need to load anything during play so the CD-ROM is free for music streaming.</div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

