			<td valign="top">
				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">The reason from SNES to PS1 games ballooned in size was because alot of SNES games used compression that was no longer needed, and then ofcourse the streamed audio and streamed video. Many games are actually very small some even tiny after stripping out streams. Ridge Racer would fit on a SNES cartridge without the CD Audio. 
<br />
<br />Starting with Dreamcast and going forward, consoles finally had optical drives fast enough (and the support for them) to do more than one thing at a time. DreamCast I remember sounded really loud because of the way it would be streaming ADX music in an open world game like Crazy Taxi where at the same time it is streaming the music it is loaded new game area as you go. Grand Theft Auto on PS2 is another good example though in a way it's a bad example cause often the DVD drive couldn't keep up and you get to an area before loading completes and it look awful. Though to be fair that game looks awful anyway.</div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

